\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Welfare weakly increases if a new product 
\begin_inset Formula $J+1$
\end_inset

 is introduced.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W^{\text{new}} & =\alpha y_{i}+\log(\underbrace{\exp(-\alpha p_{J+1})}_{\geq0}+\sum_{j=0}^{J}\exp(-\alpha p_{j}))+\gamma
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{J+1}<\infty$
\end_inset

 then welfare increases.
 The reason for this is that welfare is increasing in the size of the market
 (decreasing in the outside option).
 Increasing the number of goods in this setting means increasing the market
 size.
 The new product 
\begin_inset Formula $J+1$
\end_inset

 is stealing market share equally from all other goods (IIA issue of iid
 errors) 
\emph on
including 
\emph default
the outside option.
 So total market size grows so welfare increases.
\end_layout

